# TypeScript Code Review Rules

## 1. Type Safety
- **Never use `any`** ŌĆö flag all occurrences. Suggest a specific type, `unknown`, or a generic.
- **No implicit `any`** ŌĆö all function parameters and return types must be explicitly typed.
- **Prefer `unknown` over `any`** for truly unknown values; always narrow before use.
- **Avoid type assertions (`as`)** unless unavoidable. Require an explanatory comment when used.
- **Enforce strict null checks** ŌĆö flag patterns that ignore `null` or `undefined`.

```ts
// ŌØī Bad
function process(data: any) { ... }

// Ō£ģ Good
function process(data: ProcessInput): ProcessOutput { ... }
```

## 2. Interfaces & Types
- Use `interface` for object shapes that may be extended; use `type` for unions, intersections, and aliases.
- Avoid redundant or overlapping type declarations.
- All exported types and interfaces must have JSDoc comments.
- Flag `object`, `Object`, or `{}` as types ŌĆö require specific, named definitions.

## 3. Null & Undefined Handling
- Flag unguarded access on values that may be `null` or `undefined`.
- Suggest optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`) where appropriate.
- Flag non-null assertions (`!`) unless provably safe ŌĆö require a comment explaining why.

```ts
// ŌØī Bad
const name = user.profile.name;

// Ō£ģ Good
const name = user?.profile?.name ?? 'Anonymous';
```

## 4. Async / Await & Promises
- All `async` functions must declare an explicit return type (e.g., `Promise<User>`).
- Prefer `async/await` over `.then()/.catch()` chains.
- All `await` expressions must be inside a `try/catch` or have upstream error handling.
- Flag unhandled floating promises (no `await` and no `.catch()`).

## 5. Avoid Synchronous Methods
Never use synchronous (blocking) API variants when an async alternative exists.

### File System (`fs`)
Always use `fs/promises` instead of `*Sync` methods:
- `fs.readFileSync()` ŌåÆ `fs.promises.readFile()`
- `fs.writeFileSync()` ŌåÆ `fs.promises.writeFile()`
- `fs.mkdirSync()` ŌåÆ `fs.promises.mkdir()`
- `fs.existsSync()` ŌåÆ `fs.promises.access()`

### Child Process
Flag `execSync`, `spawnSync`, `execFileSync`. Use promisified alternatives.

### DNS
Flag synchronous DNS lookups. Use `dns/promises` instead.

### Acceptable Exceptions
- Top-level CLI scripts (single-run process)
- Jest/Vitest `globalSetup` files
- Build tooling (`scripts/*.ts`)
Always add a comment explaining why sync is acceptable.

## 6. Generics
- Encourage generics over duplicated typed functions.
- Use descriptive generic parameter names (`TItem`, `TResponse`) in complex contexts.
- Flag unconstrained generics where `extends` would improve safety.

## 7. Enums
- Prefer `const enum` for compile-time inlining when runtime reflection is not needed.
- Always use string enums over numeric enums.
- Flag mixing `enum` and union string types for the same concept.

## 8. Functions & Methods
- All exported functions must have explicit parameter types and return types.
- Flag functions longer than ~40 lines ŌĆö suggest decomposition.
- Prefer pure functions; flag undocumented side effects.

## 9. Classes
- Enforce access modifiers (`private`, `protected`, `public`) on all class members.
- Flag mutable public class properties ŌĆö prefer `readonly` or accessor methods.
- Prefer composition over inheritance; flag inheritance chains deeper than 2 levels.

## 10. Readonly & Immutability
- Use `readonly` on class properties and interface fields that must not change.
- Prefer `Readonly<T>`, `ReadonlyArray<T>`, or `as const` for immutable data.
- Flag direct mutation of function arguments.

## 11. Error Handling
- `catch` blocks must never be empty ŌĆö at minimum, log the error.
- Never catch an `Error` and re-throw as a plain string.
- Use custom error classes that extend `Error` for domain-specific errors.
- Flag `catch (e: any)` ŌĆö use `catch (e: unknown)` and narrow the type.

## 12. Imports & Modules
- Prefer named exports over default exports.
- Flag unused imports.
- Use absolute imports via `paths` in `tsconfig.json` ŌĆö flag deep relative paths (`../../..`).
- Use `import type` for type-only imports.

## 13. Utility Types
Encourage built-in TypeScript utility types (`Partial<T>`, `Pick<T, K>`, `Omit<T, K>`, `Record<K, V>`, `ReturnType<T>`, `Readonly<T>`, `NonNullable<T>`). Flag manual re-implementations.

## 14. Naming Conventions
| Construct          | Convention               | Example                     |
|-------------------|--------------------------|-----------------------------|
| Variables          | `camelCase`              | `userCount`                 |
| Functions          | `camelCase`              | `getUserById`               |
| Classes            | `PascalCase`             | `UserService`               |
| Interfaces         | `PascalCase` (no `I` prefix) | `UserProfile`           |
| Type aliases       | `PascalCase`             | `ApiResponse`               |
| Enums              | `PascalCase`             | `OrderStatus`               |
| Constants          | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`   | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`           |
| Test files         | `*.test.ts` / `*.spec.ts`| `userService.test.ts`       |

## 15. Comments & Documentation
- All exported symbols must have JSDoc comments.
- Inline comments should explain **why**, not **what**.
- Flag `TODO`/`FIXME` without a tracked issue number.

## 16. Testing
- Flag new logic with no corresponding test file or test case.
- Test files must use `.test.ts` or `.spec.ts` suffix.
- Use TypeScript-safe mocking (`jest.Mocked<T>`, `vi.mocked()`).
- Flag `as any` casts in test files.

## 17. Performance
- Flag synchronous operations inside loops that could use `Promise.all`.
- Flag unnecessary re-computation in hot paths ŌĆö suggest memoization.
- Avoid `delete` operator ŌĆö prefer `undefined` assignment or `Omit<T, K>`.

## 18. Security
- Flag string interpolation in SQL queries or shell commands ŌĆö require parameterized inputs.
- Flag hardcoded secrets, API keys, tokens, or credentials.
- Flag missing validation on user-supplied input.
- Flag `eval()`, `Function()`, or `new Function()`.

## 19. Review Checklist
### Type Safety
- [ ] No `any` without justified, commented reason
- [ ] All exported functions have explicit parameter and return types
- [ ] No unsafe non-null assertions without explanation

### Async & I/O
- [ ] No `*Sync` methods in application code
- [ ] All async code handles errors with `try/catch`
- [ ] No unhandled floating promises

### Code Quality
- [ ] No functions longer than ~40 lines without decomposition
- [ ] Naming conventions followed throughout
- [ ] No unused imports or variables
- [ ] Deep relative imports replaced with absolute path aliases

### Documentation & Tests
- [ ] All exported symbols have JSDoc comments
- [ ] No `TODO`/`FIXME` without linked issue number
- [ ] New logic has corresponding test coverage
- [ ] No `as any` casts in test files

### Security
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets or credentials
- [ ] User input is validated before use
- [ ] No raw string interpolation in SQL or shell commands
